    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26b.3-5_0001"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">3</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        Thomas <hi rend="caps">W.</hi> Wright
                        702 Sharp Building
                        18 East 11th St.
                        Kansas City 6, Mo.
                
                        July 7, 1958
                    </dateline>
                    
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Dr. John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Skyr<del/><add>i</add>m Farm,</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Route #7</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Columbia, Missouri</addrLine>
                    </address>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Dr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I want to extend warm personal greetings and best wishes to you and Mrs. Neihardt, and I hope I can see you again this fall before the semester begins. In fact it is one occasion I look forward to - this visit with you. I should have written much sooner and I hope this finds you both in good spirits. We have had plenty of rain this spring so I know your pastures have been green. I'll know for certain I would not recognize the little colt I saw a <del>h</del><add>y</add>ear ago. She must now be a beautiful young creature.</p>
                
                <p>How much do we who live in the city miss when we do not see animals grow and all the varied drama of nature unfold with the season. I spent a week in the Ozarks recently and I knew the pure pleasure of an evening of quiet without a single discordant sound.</p>
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26b.3-5_0002"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">4</fw>
                
                <fw type="authorial">- 2 -</fw>
                
                <p>My good wife said to me a while back "why don't you obtain your teaching certificate for I know you would like it." I have been thinking about her suggestion and of what you suggested in 1950. So this fall I am going to act on this suggestion because I know in my own mind I am not as happy as I could be if I were working with young people.</p>
                
                <p>One thing I have been doing has been accumulating much historical data on the frontier forts with special reference to Fort Robinson. In the library of Denver, Colorado, a while back I went through their splendid historical collection; and in Omaha I searched through the files of the Nebraska Historical Journal. All this material I plan to incorporate into a comprehensive article which will include a study of Crazy Horse after his surrender.</p>
                
                <p>It is good to share my thoughts with a friend as you are to me. Peace be with you and your lovely wife.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Very sincerely,</salute>
                
                    <signed>Thomas W. Wright</signed>
                
                    <signed>Thomas W. Wright</signed>
                </closer>
                
